  "prompt": "How do you determine the Lewis structure of SO2?",
  "response": "To determine the Lewis structure of sulfur dioxide (SO\u2082), follow these steps:\n\n1. **Count the total number of valence electrons:**\n   - Sulfur (S) is in Group 16 (or 6A) of the periodic table, so it has 6 valence electrons.\n   - Each oxygen (O) is also in Group 16 and has 6 valence electrons.\n   - Total valence electrons = 6 (S) + 2 \u00d7 6 (O) = 18.\n\n2. **Determine the central atom:**\n   - Sulfur is less electronegative than oxygen, so it will be the central atom.\n\n3. **Draw the skeletal structure:**\n   - Place the sulfur atom in the center and connect it to the two oxygen atoms with single bonds.\n   - Each single bond uses 2 electrons, so 4 electrons are used in forming the two bonds.\n\n4. **Distribute the remaining electrons:**\n   - Remaining electrons = 18 (total) - 4 (used in bonds) = 14.\n   - First, complete the octets of the outer atoms (oxygen atoms). Each oxygen needs 6 more electrons (since they already have 2 from the bond).\n   - Add 6 electrons to each oxygen atom as lone pairs, using 12 electrons.\n   - Remaining electrons = 14 - 12 = 2.\n\n5. **Assign the remaining electrons to the central atom:**\n   - Place the remaining 2 electrons on the sulfur as a lone pair.\n\n6. **Check for octet compliance:**\n   - Sulfur has 2 lone pairs and 2 bonding pairs, totaling 8 electrons, which satisfies the octet rule.\n   - Each oxygen has 2 lone pairs and 1 bonding pair, totaling 8 electrons, also satisfying the octet rule.\n\n7. **Consider resonance structures:**\n   - In reality, SO\u2082 has resonance structures due to the delocalization of electrons. This means that the double bond can be between sulfur and either oxygen atom, with the other having a single bond and a lone pair. The actual structure is a hybrid of these resonance forms.\n\nThe final Lewis structure of SO\u2082 can be represented as:\n\n```\n    O\n    ||\nS\n    ||\n    O\n```\n\nEach oxygen has two lone pairs, and the sulfur has one lone pair. The double bond can be with either oxygen, indicating resonance.",
